	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>byuu</b> [ Sun Feb 23, 2014 8:27 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: MSU1 Specs</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />&gt; Thanks for the link. Don't know if it's worth emulating it... is it some sort of long lost masterpiece?<br /><br />It was the initial prototype prior to MSU1. I really liked the name a lot more, too. The idea back then was to allow it to work on the SNES expansion port (B-bus.) But we didn't want to require special cart hardware to allow direct transfers from 21fx-&gt;PPU VRAM, so we changed things to run on the A-bus.<br /><br />Also took ikari's advice in mind that the shift register system was likely to prove more difficult to implement in hardware, and expanded the register layout from three to eight registers.<br /><br />&gt; I hope I got right: The Skillrex demo is another MSU1 program, isn't it?<br /><br />It doesn't exist yet, but it could easily be made. It's why we don't want two implementations to behave differently.<br /><br />&gt; and twice in this thread<br /><br />Yes, that was my fault. These changes took place in 2011. I don't have the best memory, so I made a mistake in writing, but the source code implementation remained the same and correct. Initial volume in early 2011 was 255. Volume in late 2011 was changed to 0. That was the only time it actually changed.<br /><br />&gt; that was annoying you?<br /><br />Only a little, because it may lead to fragmentation (WAVs are certainly easier for casual users to produce.) This one's really tough.<br /><br />The MSU1 register interface and expected behavior is very well defined.<br /><br />But when it comes to naming files and music formats ... this is a real toss-up. I really don't know how to make a universally compatible format here. Some people are going to want to distribute music tracks as MP3 or OGG. Some are going to want to distribute the movies as AVIs that are decoded and stored into the MSU1 data file. Some people are going to want game folders for higan/bsnes, some are going to want game files for other emulators.<br /><br />Technically speaking, you can add support in no$sns to play a 96KHz, 24-bit, 7.1 surround MP3 file for a track. If that music file is present, it will work just fine with any MSU1 game. But that track won't work in higan or sd2snes. The same is true of a WAV track.<br /><br />And with higan/bsnes, I really like my manifest system, which lets you specify the filename of each track. Let's say you're a casual user, and you want to swap out audio tracks with alternate selections (ocremix has dozens of versions of the same songs played on different instruments, for example.) Which of the following would be more intuitive to you?<br /><br />Option A:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Legend of Zelda, The - A Link to the Past-0.pcm<br />Legend of Zelda, The - A Link to the Past-1.pcm<br />Legend of Zelda, The - A Link to the Past-2.pcm<br />Legend of Zelda, The - A Link to the Past-3.pcm<br />Legend of Zelda, The - A Link to the Past-4.pcm</div><br /><br />Option B:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Track 01 - Opening Credits.mp3<br />Track 02 - Boss Battle.mp3<br />Track 03 - Overworld Theme.mp3<br />Track 04 - Dungeon Theme.mp3<br />Track 05 - Ending Credits.mp3</div><br />(no, I don't support MP3s. It's an example.)<br /><br />But option B forces people to use my manifest files in BML format. So it's probably not going to happen on the sd2snes.<br /><br />So I really don't know what to do here.<br /><br />This has already been a problem. It's why Super Road Blaster doesn't run directly on the latest higan release.<br /><br />We need to absolutely standardize on a system here, humbly ask d4s to update his download page, and make the standard the required distribution model. But that's going to be a topic that is highly contentious and goes on for months.<br /><br />The only thing I can think of is to make a really fancy tool that takes the input data in a variety of supported formats, and you then choose to produce a working copy of the game that runs on a given implementation: be it higan/bsnes, no$sns, or sd2snes. This tool would need to run on Windows, OS X, Linux and BSD at a minimum.<br /><br />There's just no way sd2snes is ever going to play back that hypothetical 96KHz 7.1 surround MP3 directly, nor any way higan's ever going to run a game without a manifest board description.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


