		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">byuu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">&gt; I hope I got right: The Skrillex demo is another MSU1 program, isn't it?<br />It doesn't exist yet, but it could easily be made. It's why we don't want two implementations to behave differently.</div><br />Okay, different implementations are bad, no question. But just to push this a bit more:<br />- Akira exists, and works on sd2snes, but doesn't work with volume=00h.<br />- Skrillex doesn't exist, but if it would exist, then wouldn't work with volume=FFh.<br />- All other existing games/demos work with either volume setting.<br />Of that two initial settings, I would still vote for the one that is compatible with existing software.<br />I am not saying because I voting against your specs, or because I am voting for the sd2snes implementation.<br />I am just voting for the variant that appears to be more user-friendly.<br />Any chance that you could consider that idea?<br /><br />I would like to stay compatible with higan and sd2snes implementations, and also would like to stay compatible with that demo. If that isn't possible then I could probably...<br />- detect the old demo.sfc engine and switch to a pre-MSU1 emulation mode for that specific movie player.<br />- detect any msu games that play audio with uninitialized volume and display an optional &quot;this would work only on older MSU1-implementations&quot; warning message.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">byuu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">&gt; and twice in this thread<br />Yes, that was my fault.</div><br />No problem.<br /><br />I was considering .wav's only to get Super Mario Odyssee working, but I didn't really like the idea to go into .wav support either. And now we have a .pcm version of that game, I am not considering .wav support any longer.<br /><br />For now I would recommend staying with the existing .pcm and .msu files without compression. If there are hundreds of MSU games at some point in future then it might be worth to go into compression. Although at that time, internet may so fast that nobody cares about 4GB downloads. On a side note: At that time people might use movie demos that are longer than 2 minutes. So sample rate should be accurate enough for longer movies (of course within reason, a quartz inaccuracy of 1 second per day or week would be rather irrelevant).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
