	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />&lt;nocash&gt; Any chance that you could consider that idea?<br /><br />I would have to change the specification yet again. And it's also more complicated to say &quot;all regs default to zero EXCEPT volume which is 255&quot; than it is to say &quot;all regs default to zero.&quot;<br /><br />I'm really having a hard time understanding why it's such a big deal to stay compatible with a single tech demo. ikari said he was going to release an update that sets the volume register. Nobody is actually using that tech demo ROM.<br /><br />You know, the Power Slide FX demo doesn't work unless you initialize SRAM to 0x00. I don't have a special case in higan to run it. It remains broken, because it is broken by design. If the battery fails on that proto cart and you replace it, the game won't run anymore. We don't have to have 100% perfect compatibility.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">- detect the old demo.sfc engine and switch to a pre-MSU1 emulation mode for that specific movie player.<br />- detect any msu games that play audio with uninitialized volume and display an optional &quot;this would work only on older MSU1-implementations&quot; warning message.</div><br /><br />Both of these sound like very good ideas to me. I hope they wouldn't be too much trouble to you.<br /><br />&lt;nocash&gt; And now we have a .pcm version of that game, I am not considering .wav support any longer.<br /><br />Yeah, so let's do the same with the Akira demo.<br /><br />&lt;nocash&gt; For now I would recommend staying with the existing .pcm and .msu files without compression.<br /><br />I definitely think that's how all emulators and hardware implementations should run the games, no doubt. Requiring an emulator to contain multiple video and audio codecs is completely unacceptable.<br /><br />The idea is that you would combine: compressed download + my special program (maybe distribute them together as one download), and when run, it spits out a game in .msu + .pcm format that all of our implementations can play. It also handles the manifest / game folder / filename differences.<br /><br />My only concern is that people won't share a CD-audio game patch that requires a 700MB download, but they are much more likely to share one that requires a 20MB download.<br /><br />&lt;nocash&gt; On a side note: At that time people might use movie demos that are longer than 2 minutes.<br /><br />True. It also has to exist. I think the most common use case now is bringing over anime intros from SNES ports.<br />Like this video: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gn_jXf7FHGA">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gn_jXf7FHGA</a><!-- m --><br />It adds the PS1 port's FMV into the SNES port. The nice FMV sequence with no loading delays.<br /><br />&lt;KungFuFurby&gt; I personally was considering not distributing raw .pcm files, but instead make two .flac files for each piece of music (opening and loop) with some exceptions<br /><br />Well, on the opening + loop part ... the way that works with PCM is nice and easy.<br /><br />Combine the two files, and set the loop sample# to the total number of samples in the opening song.<br /><br />If you want them separate and write a conversion tool to turn this into PCM, that's fine I suppose.<br /><br />I am just hoping that whatever formats and whatever converter ends up being used, is available on every major platform. I run FreeBSD, so if you distribute a game in FLAC only, I'd have to write my own converter to run your game.<br /><br />I definitely understand nocash's concerns here, but I think people are going to distribute compressed files whether we want them to or not. It's probably better for us to do it right than to have several ad-hoc, Windows-only converters. (not saying yours would be Windows-only, but in general most would be.)

		

		</td>
	</tr>
