		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">byuu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">&lt;KungFuFurby&gt; I personally was considering not distributing raw .pcm files, but instead make two .flac files for each piece of music (opening and loop) with some exceptions<br /><br />Well, on the opening + loop part ... the way that works with PCM is nice and easy.<br /><br />Combine the two files, and set the loop sample# to the total number of samples in the opening song.<br /><br />If you want them separate and write a conversion tool to turn this into PCM, that's fine I suppose.<br /><br />I am just hoping that whatever formats and whatever converter ends up being used, is available on every major platform. I run FreeBSD, so if you distribute a game in FLAC only, I'd have to write my own converter to run your game.<br /><br />I definitely understand nocash's concerns here, but I think people are going to distribute compressed files whether we want them to or not. It's probably better for us to do it right than to have several ad-hoc, Windows-only converters. (not saying yours would be Windows-only, but in general most would be.)</div><br /><br />I myself don't use Windows by default (so far, I use it as a debugger for safety reasons). I'm actually wondering what lossless compression formats would be a good idea... my first instinct is FLAC, although I'm open to other formats.

		

